		<pubDate>Tue, 12 Aug 2014 13:17:24 +0000</pubDate>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">https://jamesclear-com.uar9g7bv-liquidwebsites.com/?p=6042#comment-10816</guid>

					<description><![CDATA[Great post.  As I read, what struck me was the use of music as a creative outlet for therapy or serenity. My question is whether this works for nonmusically inclined people. I like to listen to music, but not with any sense of need. I can be happy with silence or the sounds of nature.  For me, words are my way out of tangled troubles.  Writing out my thoughts, writing a letter, an essay, even a text or email to a friend can help.  Reading is also a way to lose myself, but that is more escapist and doesn&#039;t tend to resolve things.  Talking with a true friend is very very helpful, but having a true friend to be open with is also very rare for me.  Music, for my soul&#039;s healing, is a caring friend and words.]]></description>
			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>Great post.  As I read, what struck me was the use of music as a creative outlet for therapy or serenity. My question is whether this works for nonmusically inclined people. I like to listen to music, but not with any sense of need. I can be happy with silence or the sounds of nature.  For me, words are my way out of tangled troubles.  Writing out my thoughts, writing a letter, an essay, even a text or email to a friend can help.  Reading is also a way to lose myself, but that is more escapist and doesn&#8217;t tend to resolve things.  Talking with a true friend is very very helpful, but having a true friend to be open with is also very rare for me.  Music, for my soul&#8217;s healing, is a caring friend and words.</p>
]]></content:encoded>
		
